<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>HOUSE OF LORDS ECONOMIC AFFAIRS COMMITTEE</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">FBA0012/13-14</span></p><h1 style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">HMRC—Written evidence</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">OTS PARTNERSHIP REVIEW</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Taxation of partnerships</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Partnerships are transparent for most tax purposes.  Partners are liable to tax on their share of the profits of the business on essentially the same basis as they would be taxed on profits of a business carried on alone.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This means that businesses have a choice between using a structure where tax liability rests with the business entity (e.g. a company), or a tax transparent partnership or Limited Liability Partnership (LLP).  When the Limited Liability Partnership structure was introduced, tax transparent treatment was provided in response to business views.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Partners are taxed on the full amount of the partnership profits, just as sole traders or companies are taxed on the full amount of business profits.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Partnerships make their own decisions on how much of their profits they wish to retain or distribute (subject to any relevant company law provisions applicable to LLPs), just as sole traders decide how much drawing to take from their business and companies decide distributions to shareholders. </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Where an individual partner incurs an allowable business expense, this is taken into account for tax purposes in calculating the taxable profits of the partnership business.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC believes that the current basis of taxation of partnerships is fair.  It follows from the principle of tax transparency and the general approach to taxation of business profits.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Partnerships and partners as customers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">To meet our objectives, HMRC has developed a ‘Customer-Centric Business Strategy’.  This means developing a deep understanding of our customers, so we can deliver services which are based on their needs and positively influence their behaviours.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC treats partnerships in the same way as all our other customers – we are committed to helping partnerships and partners get their tax right and treating them fairly.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC Customer Survey results indicate that over 80% of those carrying on business in partnership reported being well treated by HMRC staff in their dealings with HMRC, the same high score as for sole traders.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Organisation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC has a Business Customer and Strategy Directorate, led by a Senior Civil Servant, which works with other parts of HMRC and external stakeholders to build our customer understanding and improve the customer experience for all our business customers, including partnerships.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">For the largest partnerships, HMRC invests in a resource-intensive, relationship-managed service, because the money and complexity involved make this the most cost-effective way of getting the right tax agreed early with these customers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC also has a dedicated, specialist Partnership unit in our Local Compliance area of the business,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with the capability to deal with complex issues and provide advice and support to operational and compliance colleagues on issues in connection with our partnership customers’ tax affairs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Tax administration</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC is committed to reducing administrative burdens on our business and other customers, and improving our service to them.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC intends to build on the Autumn Statement 2012 investment in digital services, expanding these services so that it is easier and cheaper for customers to deal with HMRC as well as reducing costs for HMRC.  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">To make the tax system more efficient, transparent and less burdensome HMRC will significantly expand the online services it offers over the next three years.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">An example of a current digital project is “Your tax account” – an online tax dashboard which will be available to individual partners to help them manage their tax affairs. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">One of the aims of investing in information technology is so that we only have to ask for information once, for use across our systems.  For partnerships, our strategy for the future is to make the fullest use of data from partnerships and collect less information from individual partners.  (Just as by collecting information from employers through the Pay as You Earn system, we have reduced the information we need from individual employees).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Compliance</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Most partnerships and partners want to get their tax right, and HMRC is committed to helping them to do so.  But, at the same time, HMRC is also relentless in pursuing the minority who bend or break the rules.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC undertakes comprehensive risk assessment (including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to identify</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> inconsistencies between partnership and individual partner returns).  Enquires and other interventions are pursued to collect the right amount of tax.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Tax simplification</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Government is committed to simplifying the tax system to ensure that taxpayers can understand and comply with their obligations.  HMRC is actively supporting implementation of the Government’s priorities on tax simplification by working closely with the Office of Tax Simplification (OTS) on their reviews.  The Tax Assurance Commissioner and second Permanent Secretary, Edward Troup, sits on the OTS Board.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC believes that working together with the OTS, and in consultation with our customers, tax professionals and other stakeholders, it will be able to deliver simplification for customers; tackle legislative complexity; and simplify and streamline tax administration.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The OTS Interim Report on the taxation of partnerships</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Government is grateful for the work the OTS is doing to further the simplification of the tax system.  The OTS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> put forward a number of proposals in their interim report on the taxation of partnerships which the Government will be considering in detail.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Government will make a formal response to the report in the 2014 Budget.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">TAXATION OF PARTNERSHIPS: DRAFT FINANCE BILL 2014 PROVISIONS</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Origins</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The possibility of conducting a formal review of certain aspects of the tax rules on partnerships (including limited liability partnerships (LLPs)) was first mentioned at Autumn Statement 2012 as part of a Written Ministerial Statement (WMS) announcing the closure of a tax avoidance scheme involving partnership tax rules. The WMS stated that the Government would consider partnership taxation as part of its review of high risk areas of the tax code.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This was followed by a formal announcement at Budget 2013 indicating that the Government would consult on introducing legislation effective from April 2014 to:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">remove the presumption of self-employment for “Salaried Members” of LLPs; and  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">prevent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> tax-motivated allocations of business profits or losses in partnerships (including LLPs), particularly in relation to partnerships with both individual and company members (“mixed membership partnerships”). </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Consultation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC consulted stakeholders informally between the run-up to Budget 2013 and the publication of the formal consultation document in May 2013.  The evidence gathered at this stage informed the consultation proposals and the Government’s decision to introduce legislative changes. The formal consultation ran for 12 weeks ending in early August, attracting about 110 written responses. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Autumn Statement 2013 reaffirmed that the G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">overnment would take forward the proposals as modified following consideration of the consultation responses and that t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he changes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">would take effect from April 2014 as previously announced. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Draft Finance Bill 2014 clauses and guidance were published in December for technical consultation, which will close on 4 February 2014.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Associated changes to the National Insurance contributions (NICs) legislation in relation to Salaried Members and alternative investment fund managers are being introduced under the NICs Bill 2013 and these will take effect from 6 April 2014.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Costings</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Budget 2013 announcement stated that significant tax revenues were at risk from these tax-motivated arrangements.  Information obtained during the consultation showed that the use of mixed membership structures was far more widespread amongst the alternative investment fund managers (typically hedge </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">funds) who operate as a partnership than originally expected. The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">costings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> certified by the Office of Budget Responsibility and published at Autumn Statement (AS) 2013 were accordingly increased as follows (with all extra yield attributable to the investment fund manager sector):</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:446.4pt"><tr style="height:10.15pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:79.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Exchequer Impact (£millions)</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:61.8pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2013-14</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:62.6pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2014-15</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:60.9pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2015-16</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:64.35pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2016-17</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:62.6pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2017-18</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:55.05pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2018-19</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:79.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Budget  13</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:61.8pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nil</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:62.6pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">+125</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom